CKUT.about: CKUT is a non-profit, campus/community radio station based at McGill University in Montreal. CKUT provides alternative music, news and spoken word programming to the city of Montreal, surrounding areas, and around the world 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. Hear us at 90.3 MHz on the FM dial or listen online, where we also store archives of every show that hits the airwaves. CKUT has been on the FM airwaves since 1987, with roots going back to McGill's radio club, which was founded in 1921, and CFRM, a cable radio station that broadcast out of the basement of the Shatner Building on McGill campus.
CKUT.name: CKUT
CKUT.nowPlayingDescription: Butcher T's Noon Time Cuts provides intervie...
CKUT.nowPlayingDescriptionLong: Butcher T's Noon Time Cuts provides interviews from international/local artists and a wide variety of music genres from Old/New School, Soul/R&B, Hip Hop, Funk, and House. This program also airs the rhythms of Caribbean and Latin music including Reggae, Soca, Zouk, Salsa, Bachata, etc., just to name a few. Featuring legendary DJ Butcher T, Noon Time Cuts began in 1992 and showed Montreal what a real Urban Programme could be like.  Butcher T lets the music flow and plays whatever genre suits the mood - full of surprises.

Radio 80000.about: Radio 80000 is a non-commercial community radio, streaming live every day from 8am till midnight from ZIRKA in the north of Munich. DJs, musicians, producers, journalists and music lovers present an individual idea of radio that goes beyond algorithms and commercial playlists. By highlighting local scenes and welcoming guests from around the world, we aim to create a community of like-minded individuals. The studio serves as a real life meeting point for everyone to listen and hang out.

Desire Path Radio.about:
Two-channel streaming:

Channel 1 - music, where anything goes

Channel 2 - research-forward talk, education, audio documentary, experimental, and archival

[why now]

Our connection to the earth is central. Now is a critical time to return to (our) nature and get curious about the intersection of nature with different mediums and practices.

DPR is a platform for information exchange and creative expression. We need forums beyond social media and the workplace where people are encouraged to learn, experiment, and share ideas.

[why radio]

The contemporary definition of radio has evolved, expanding beyond the technology and practice of transmitting sound via electromagnetic waves. Especially in independent spaces, radio encompasses a shared culture and community.

Desire Path Radio celebrates radio broadcast as an accessible tool for discourse, entertainment, and world-building. Radio is, and always has been, radical.

[what is a desire path]

Desire paths are unofficial routes created by repeated traffic. Reflecting the patterns of human nature and both individual and collective will, these routes reveal an alternate, if not improved, way to move through space and interact with the world around us.

DIY forever.
Desire Path Radio.name: Desire Path Radip
